# Experiment Methodology

## Key Findings

- Confidence thresholding (trade top-30% signals only) *(lessons/breakeven-accuracy-before-building.md)*
- Daily resolution (breakeven drops to ~55.1%) *(lessons/breakeven-accuracy-before-building.md)*
- Maker orders (0.02% cost → breakeven ~50.7%) *(lessons/breakeven-accuracy-before-building.md)*
- Always calculate the minimum accuracy required for profitability at your target resolution and cost structure BEFORE committing to a model architecture. *(lessons/breakeven-accuracy-before-building.md)*
- `pipeline_update.py` parses stage history tables by looking for `| Stage |` followed immediately by a `|---|---|---|---|` separator row on the next line. If the markdown separator row is missing, the parser silently fails and only updates the state JSON — the markdown file gets no stage history entries. *(lessons/pipeline-table-separator-required.md)*
- `pipeline_update.py <version> show` works (reads JSON state) *(lessons/pipeline-table-separator-required.md)*
- But `pipelines/<version>.md` stage history table stays empty *(lessons/pipeline-table-separator-required.md)*
- No error message — silent fallback to JSON-only update *(lessons/pipeline-table-separator-required.md)*
- The pipeline template (`templates/pipeline.md`) should include the separator row *(lessons/pipeline-table-separator-required.md)*
- When creating new pipeline primitives, verify table structure before first update *(lessons/pipeline-table-separator-required.md)*
- Consider hardening `pipeline_update.py` to warn (not silently skip) when separator is missing *(lessons/pipeline-table-separator-required.md)*
- Static window encoding (batch of features → spike pattern → classify) wastes the SNN's temporal advantage completely. V1 collapsed to majority-class because rate coding on 1h candles gave the SNN nothing a logistic regression couldn't do. *(lessons/snn-treats-like-weird-cnn.md)*
- SNNs are fundamentally change-detectors, not classifiers. Use them for what they're good at. *(lessons/snn-treats-like-weird-cnn.md)*
- 5. **Explicit cleanup:** `del model` + `gc.collect()` + `torch.cuda.empty_cache()` after every fold. Without this, VRAM climbs ~50-100MB per experiment and never comes back. *(lessons/tiny-snn-gpu-parallelism.md)*
- **fp16/mixed precision:** BCELoss produces NaN/Inf under autocast. Models are too small to benefit anyway. *(lessons/tiny-snn-gpu-parallelism.md)*
- **Conservative worker counts:** 3-6 workers on a T4 leaves >60% of GPU idle between kernel launches. *(lessons/tiny-snn-gpu-parallelism.md)*
- **Relying on Python GC alone:** PyTorch's CUDA caching allocator holds memory even after Python objects are collected. Must explicitly call `torch.cuda.empty_cache()`. *(lessons/tiny-snn-gpu-parallelism.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/agent-reconstruction-errors-from-fragments-vs-actual-conclusions.md)*
- # Always Back Up Workspace to GitHub *(lessons/always-back-up-workspace-to-github.md)*
- Over 8 days (March 12–20), the workspace accumulated 331 tracked files: a full CLI (belam, 545 lines + 883-line index engine), 40+ Python scripts, 95 primitives, complete memory hierarchy, pipeline orchestration infrastructure. The `machinelearning/` submodule was pushed to GitHub. The workspace itself had local commits but **no remote**. *(lessons/always-back-up-workspace-to-github.md)*
- **Every file that matters must be in a repo with a remote. If it's not pushed, it doesn't exist.** *(lessons/always-back-up-workspace-to-github.md)*
- Scripts and tools must live inside the tracked workspace, not in ad-hoc PATH locations *(lessons/always-back-up-workspace-to-github.md)*
- "It's committed locally" is not a backup — it needs a remote *(lessons/always-back-up-workspace-to-github.md)*
- Check for untracked critical files regularly (things installed to PATH, cron entries, system configs) *(lessons/always-back-up-workspace-to-github.md)*
- **Heartbeat Task 6** must push both `belam-codex` and `machinelearning` repos *(lessons/always-back-up-workspace-to-github.md)*
- When creating new scripts/tools, always put them in `scripts/` and symlink to PATH — never the reverse *(lessons/always-back-up-workspace-to-github.md)*
- Periodically verify: `git remote -v` shows a remote, `git status` is clean, `git push` succeeds *(lessons/always-back-up-workspace-to-github.md)*
- The `incarnate.sh` pattern (resurrection script in the repo) should be maintained as the repo evolves *(lessons/always-back-up-workspace-to-github.md)*
- instance:main embed-primitives supermap boot-context cleanup archive-pattern *(lessons/archive-embed-primitives-when-supermap-replaces-it.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/archive-embed-primitives-when-supermap-replaces-it.md)*
- Tried spawning an extraction subagent directly from the `agent:bootstrap` hook handler. Failed — the hook fires while the new session already holds the JSONL file lock. Also discovered that `openclaw agent --agent main` with any `--session-id` still collides with the active session lock. *(lessons/auto-memory-extraction-on-bootstrap.md)*
- Also discovered that raw JSONL session files balloon to 200KB+ because tool results (file reads, etc.) get stored as full text blocks. The inline Python parser in bash grew too complex — extracted to `parse_session_transcript.py`. *(lessons/auto-memory-extraction-on-bootstrap.md)*
- **Hook → marker file → agent reads on boot → `sessions_spawn`** is the correct pattern. The hook cannot directly spawn a session for the same agent it's bootstrapping; it must defer to the agent itself. *(lessons/auto-memory-extraction-on-bootstrap.md)*
- When the hook fires on `agent:bootstrap`, write a marker file (e.g. `memory/pending_extraction.json`) with the previous session path, instance name, and persona *(lessons/auto-memory-extraction-on-bootstrap.md)*
- On session startup (AGENTS.md protocol), the agent checks for `pending_extraction.json`, spawns a subagent via `sessions_spawn`, then deletes the marker *(lessons/auto-memory-extraction-on-bootstrap.md)*
- JSONL parser must truncate text blocks to ~500 chars and cap total transcript at ~40K chars (~10K tokens) for subagent efficiency *(lessons/auto-memory-extraction-on-bootstrap.md)*
- Model alias for subagent spawns: `anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6` (not `anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-20250514`) *(lessons/auto-memory-extraction-on-bootstrap.md)*
- Extract complex inline Python from bash scripts into dedicated `.py` files early — bash+python hybrids get unmaintainable fast *(lessons/auto-memory-extraction-on-bootstrap.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/boot-context-missing-command-grammar-reference.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/boot-context-pipeline-status-can-be-stale.md)*
- infrastructure agents orchestration pattern *(lessons/checkpoint-and-resume-pattern.md)*
- Agent memory files survive session resets (they're on disk, not in session context) *(lessons/checkpoint-and-resume-pattern.md)*
- Partial artifacts (design docs, notebooks) also survive on shared filesystem *(lessons/checkpoint-and-resume-pattern.md)*
- Each resume builds on accumulated checkpoints — the agent gets smarter about what's left to do *(lessons/checkpoint-and-resume-pattern.md)*
- This pattern is tier 2 of 3. Full chain: *(lessons/checkpoint-and-resume-pattern.md)*
- 2. **Checkpoint-and-resume (10 min)** — this pattern, saves partial work and re-wakes with context *(lessons/checkpoint-and-resume-pattern.md)*
- Don't use deterministic session IDs (UUID5) hoping to "continue" a session — OpenClaw sessions accumulate context, leading to confusion. Always use fresh UUID4 + memory files for continuity. *(lessons/checkpoint-and-resume-pattern.md)*
- R0 supermap for orientation (full workspace in ~60 lines) *(lessons/codex-engine-feels-native-at-v1.md)*
- `t1 2 9` for surgical field zoom (3 lines instead of reading a whole file) *(lessons/codex-engine-feels-native-at-v1.md)*
- `t1 B` for body inspection when needed *(lessons/codex-engine-feels-native-at-v1.md)*
- `-g t1 --depth 2` for provenance tracing (saw 4 decisions converging into the task) *(lessons/codex-engine-feels-native-at-v1.md)*
- `-e t1 2 'active'` for status change with F-labeled diff *(lessons/codex-engine-feels-native-at-v1.md)*
- Pin detection (`R📌R4`) eliminated a redundant 30-token render *(lessons/codex-engine-feels-native-at-v1.md)*
- Default to Codex Engine for all primitive access going forward *(lessons/codex-engine-feels-native-at-v1.md)*
- Body editing is the main gap preventing full lock — prioritize in polish phase *(lessons/codex-engine-feels-native-at-v1.md)*
- The attention-native feedback language (F/R labels, pins) compounds over a session — more value the longer the conversation runs *(lessons/codex-engine-feels-native-at-v1.md)*
- This validates the "limit soul read-write access" task (t4) as viable once body editing is complete *(lessons/codex-engine-feels-native-at-v1.md)*
- Design principle: the correct path should also be the easiest path — friction elimination beats discipline every time *(lessons/codex-engine-feels-native-at-v1.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/codex-render-test-mode-dulwich-session-branch.md)*
- # Continuous Input Mode Consistently Outperforms Spike Mode *(lessons/continuous-input-beats-spike-mode.md)*
- Across all V2 model variants (SNN and LSTM, all schemes, all sizes), passing raw Gaussian activation values (continuous mode) to the SNN outperforms Bernoulli-sampled spike trains (spike mode). *(lessons/continuous-input-beats-spike-mode.md)*
- **Implication:** For financial SNN architectures, use continuous (graded) input by default. Reserve true spiking input for neuromorphic hardware deployment where it's required. Deterministic evaluation (continuous mode) is essential for reliable metrics — stochastic eval makes all accuracy and Sharpe measurements unreliable. *(lessons/continuous-input-beats-spike-mode.md)*
- V2 showed population coding (Scheme 0) outperforming delta encoding (Scheme A) by ~2pp accuracy. But population coding uses 35 input neurons (7 features × 5 Gaussian neurons) while delta uses 14 (7 features × 2 channels pos/neg). More inputs → more first-layer capacity → potentially better performance regardless of encoding quality. *(lessons/control-input-dimensionality-in-encoding-comparisons.md)*
- **This is a critical confound.** Until controlled, the statement "population coding outperforms delta encoding" should be qualified as "population coding with higher input dimensionality outperforms delta encoding with lower input dimensionality." *(lessons/control-input-dimensionality-in-encoding-comparisons.md)*
- **General principle:** When comparing encoding schemes, always match input dimensionality or include it as an explicit factor in the experimental design. Otherwise you're comparing encoding quality AND model capacity simultaneously. *(lessons/control-input-dimensionality-in-encoding-comparisons.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/coordinate-dispatch-without-r-prefix.md)*
- instance:main codex-engine e3 e2 namespace design-pattern *(lessons/e3-chains-e2-after-namespace-registration.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/e3-chains-e2-after-namespace-registration.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/legacy-view-command-primitives-redundant-after-engine.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/memory-extract-hook-session-file-detection-mismatch.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/memory-extraction-misses-design-convergence-in-conversation.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/openclaw-fixed-context-injection-list.md)*
- Running autonomous multi-pipeline dependency resolution (Engine V2 → Orch V3 → Engine V3). The orchestration engine V2 (`orchestration_engine.py`) handles all gate logic, stage transitions, and dispatch payload generation, but doesn't natively spawn subagents — the spawn call must be issued from the main session. *(lessons/orchestration-dispatch-payload-spawn-relay.md)*
- Used `orchestration_engine.py dispatch-payload <version> <agent>` to get a structured JSON spawn payload with the full task prompt, memory protocol, pre/post actions, and stage context. Then passed that payload directly into `sessions_spawn` as the `task` parameter. The orchestration engine tracked state; the main session acted as spawn relay. *(lessons/orchestration-dispatch-payload-spawn-relay.md)*
- `dispatch-payload` is the bridge between orchestration engine logic and sessions_spawn: the engine generates the *what*, the main session executes the *how*. This is the interim pattern until Orch V3 closes the autonomous relay loop. *(lessons/orchestration-dispatch-payload-spawn-relay.md)*
- This pattern makes the orchestration engine the single source of truth for pipeline state while keeping spawn logic in the session layer. Orch V3's automation goal is to close this loop so no manual relay is needed. *(lessons/orchestration-dispatch-payload-spawn-relay.md)*
- The legacy system's last act was building its own replacement. The `codex-cockpit` plugin (R-label injection via `before_prompt_build`) was also built in the same session, proving the hook architecture the orchestration engine now uses. *(lessons/orchestration-engine-v1-self-built-through-legacy-pipeline.md)*
- **Use the system you're replacing to build its replacement.** The legacy orchestration scripts were good enough to autonomously produce a first draft of the new engine. The manual pass added the architectural vision. The merge produced something better than either alone. Self-referential bootstrapping works when the existing system is functional. *(lessons/orchestration-engine-v1-self-built-through-legacy-pipeline.md)*
- When building infrastructure replacements, run the old system one last time to produce the first draft *(lessons/orchestration-engine-v1-self-built-through-legacy-pipeline.md)*
- Parallel manual + automated passes catch different issues (auto-run found implementation gaps, manual pass found architectural gaps) *(lessons/orchestration-engine-v1-self-built-through-legacy-pipeline.md)*
- Phase 2 refinement that merges two independent passes is more robust than a single linear pipeline *(lessons/orchestration-engine-v1-self-built-through-legacy-pipeline.md)*
- The pattern extends: v2 of the orchestration engine should be built THROUGH v1, proving v1 works *(lessons/orchestration-engine-v1-self-built-through-legacy-pipeline.md)*
- The equilibrium SNN should be re-explored with a phasic-dominant architecture: strong phasic pathway, weak/optional tonic pathway. Combine with Scheme B regression output for the confidence-weighted abstention mechanism. *(lessons/phasic-only-ablation-wins-equilibrium.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/pipeline-dashboard-watch-flag-vs-linux-watch.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/pipeline-orchestrate-blocking-agent-wake.md)*
- The `archive_pipeline()` function in `launch_pipeline.py` was correctly updating the pipeline `.md` file to `status: archived`, but never updating the corresponding `_state.json`. As a result, archived pipelines (orch-v1, orch-v2, build-equilibrium-snn, stack-specialists, v4, v4-deep-analysis) continued to show as active at session boot. Fixed by patching the archive function to also write `status: archived` to the state JSON. *(lessons/pipeline-state-json-not-synced-on-archive.md)*
- Any pipeline state mutation must update **both** the pipeline `.md` AND the `_state.json` file — they are separate stores and both must stay in sync. *(lessons/pipeline-state-json-not-synced-on-archive.md)*
- When adding new pipeline state transitions (archive, pause, reset), always update `_state.json` alongside the `.md` file. The `launch_pipeline.py` archive function now does this, but new mutation functions must follow the same pattern. *(lessons/pipeline-state-json-not-synced-on-archive.md)*
- # plugin-allowlist-must-be-updated-on-plugin-retire *(lessons/plugin-allowlist-must-be-updated-on-plugin-retire.md)*
- Retiring a plugin by renaming its directory to `.disabled` prevents OpenClaw from loading the plugin code, but `openclaw.json` still lists it in `plugins.allow`. When an agent is spawned, OpenClaw validates `plugins.allow` against actually-loadable plugins and fails with a config error if a listed plugin is missing. *(lessons/plugin-allowlist-must-be-updated-on-plugin-retire.md)*
- After renaming `pipeline-context` → `pipeline-context.disabled`, the next heartbeat attempted to dispatch the codex-engine-v3 architect agent. The agent failed to spawn because OpenClaw config validation rejected the stale `pipeline-context` entry in `plugins.allow`. Fixed by removing it from the allowlist. *(lessons/plugin-allowlist-must-be-updated-on-plugin-retire.md)*
