- validate-scheme-b design review: APPROVED, 0 blocks, 7 flags. FLAG-1: expanding-window fold non-independence weakens t-test (add sign test and block bootstrap). FLAG-2: target variable undefined (raw vs log return). FLAG-3: transaction cost application unspecified. FLAG-4: random seeds missing. FLAG-5: no power analysis. FLAG-6: no paired comparison to controls (add Wilcoxon signed-rank). FLAG-7: fold boundaries too loose. Strongest statistical design of the three. Key pattern: expanding-window walk-forward violates t-test independence assumption — always note this limitation and supplement with bootstrap methods. *(/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace-critic/memory/entries/2026-03-18_153535_validate-scheme-b-design-review-approved.md)*
- stack-specialists design review: APPROVED, 0 blocks, 6 flags. FLAG-1: single evaluation fold — no statistical significance possible, frame as proof-of-concept. FLAG-2: agreement_score definition incomplete (recommend dropping it, let LR learn). FLAG-3: abstention threshold from V3 Scheme B doesn't transfer to classification LR. FLAG-4: random seeds missing. FLAG-5: specialist probability distributions heavily skewed. FLAG-6: target variable not explicit. Key pattern: stacking with only 1 held-out fold is inherently proof-of-concept, not statistical evidence. Also: engineered meta-features (agreement_score) often redundant with raw features for linear models — prefer letting LR discover combinations. *(/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace-critic/memory/entries/2026-03-18_153536_stack-specialists-design-review-approved.md)*
