- `openclaw agent --agent main` always routes to the active main session. Use `sessions_spawn` from within the coordinator for ephemeral subagent work. *(lessons/openclaw-agent-routes-to-active-session.md)*
- **Don't:** Spawn `openclaw agent --agent main` from background scripts while coordinator is active *(lessons/openclaw-agent-routes-to-active-session.md)*
- **Do:** Use `sessions_spawn` tool for parallel subagent work (proven: 8 parallel Sonnet subagents, ~10s each) *(lessons/openclaw-agent-routes-to-active-session.md)*
- **Alternative:** Use `--agent architect` or `--agent critic` if CLI spawning is needed (they have separate session spaces) *(lessons/openclaw-agent-routes-to-active-session.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/openclaw-fixed-context-injection-list.md)*
- Building the `codex-cockpit` workspace plugin to use the `before_prompt_build` hook *(lessons/openclaw-plugin-definepluginentry-import-path.md)*
- for per-turn supermap injection. First attempt at writing the plugin entry used *(lessons/openclaw-plugin-definepluginentry-import-path.md)*
- Inspecting stock plugins (diffs, device-pair) revealed the correct pattern: *(lessons/openclaw-plugin-definepluginentry-import-path.md)*
- Import type `OpenClawPluginApi` from `openclaw/plugin-sdk/<submodule>` *(lessons/openclaw-plugin-definepluginentry-import-path.md)*
- Export a plain object (not a function wrapper) with `id`, `name`, `description`, and `register(api)` *(lessons/openclaw-plugin-definepluginentry-import-path.md)*
- **Do NOT use `definePluginEntry`** — it is not exposed in the plugin SDK surface *(lessons/openclaw-plugin-definepluginentry-import-path.md)*
- Workspace plugins must export a plain object with `{ id, name, description, register(api) }` and import from `openclaw/plugin-sdk/<specific-submodule>`; `definePluginEntry` is NOT a valid SDK export. *(lessons/openclaw-plugin-definepluginentry-import-path.md)*
- Every time a new OpenClaw workspace plugin is written: *(lessons/openclaw-plugin-definepluginentry-import-path.md)*
- Running autonomous multi-pipeline dependency resolution (Engine V2 → Orch V3 → Engine V3). The orchestration engine V2 (`orchestration_engine.py`) handles all gate logic, stage transitions, and dispatch payload generation, but doesn't natively spawn subagents — the spawn call must be issued from the main session. *(lessons/orchestration-dispatch-payload-spawn-relay.md)*
- Used `orchestration_engine.py dispatch-payload <version> <agent>` to get a structured JSON spawn payload with the full task prompt, memory protocol, pre/post actions, and stage context. Then passed that payload directly into `sessions_spawn` as the `task` parameter. The orchestration engine tracked state; the main session acted as spawn relay. *(lessons/orchestration-dispatch-payload-spawn-relay.md)*
- `dispatch-payload` is the bridge between orchestration engine logic and sessions_spawn: the engine generates the *what*, the main session executes the *how*. This is the interim pattern until Orch V3 closes the autonomous relay loop. *(lessons/orchestration-dispatch-payload-spawn-relay.md)*
- This pattern makes the orchestration engine the single source of truth for pipeline state while keeping spawn logic in the session layer. Orch V3's automation goal is to close this loop so no manual relay is needed. *(lessons/orchestration-dispatch-payload-spawn-relay.md)*
- The legacy system's last act was building its own replacement. The `codex-cockpit` plugin (R-label injection via `before_prompt_build`) was also built in the same session, proving the hook architecture the orchestration engine now uses. *(lessons/orchestration-engine-v1-self-built-through-legacy-pipeline.md)*
- **Use the system you're replacing to build its replacement.** The legacy orchestration scripts were good enough to autonomously produce a first draft of the new engine. The manual pass added the architectural vision. The merge produced something better than either alone. Self-referential bootstrapping works when the existing system is functional. *(lessons/orchestration-engine-v1-self-built-through-legacy-pipeline.md)*
- When building infrastructure replacements, run the old system one last time to produce the first draft *(lessons/orchestration-engine-v1-self-built-through-legacy-pipeline.md)*
- Parallel manual + automated passes catch different issues (auto-run found implementation gaps, manual pass found architectural gaps) *(lessons/orchestration-engine-v1-self-built-through-legacy-pipeline.md)*
- Phase 2 refinement that merges two independent passes is more robust than a single linear pipeline *(lessons/orchestration-engine-v1-self-built-through-legacy-pipeline.md)*
- The pattern extends: v2 of the orchestration engine should be built THROUGH v1, proving v1 works *(lessons/orchestration-engine-v1-self-built-through-legacy-pipeline.md)*
- The equilibrium SNN should be re-explored with a phasic-dominant architecture: strong phasic pathway, weak/optional tonic pathway. Combine with Scheme B regression output for the confidence-weighted abstention mechanism. *(lessons/phasic-only-ablation-wins-equilibrium.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/pipeline-dashboard-watch-flag-vs-linux-watch.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/pipeline-orchestrate-blocking-agent-wake.md)*
- The `archive_pipeline()` function in `launch_pipeline.py` was correctly updating the pipeline `.md` file to `status: archived`, but never updating the corresponding `_state.json`. As a result, archived pipelines (orch-v1, orch-v2, build-equilibrium-snn, stack-specialists, v4, v4-deep-analysis) continued to show as active at session boot. Fixed by patching the archive function to also write `status: archived` to the state JSON. *(lessons/pipeline-state-json-not-synced-on-archive.md)*
- Any pipeline state mutation must update **both** the pipeline `.md` AND the `_state.json` file — they are separate stores and both must stay in sync. *(lessons/pipeline-state-json-not-synced-on-archive.md)*
- When adding new pipeline state transitions (archive, pause, reset), always update `_state.json` alongside the `.md` file. The `launch_pipeline.py` archive function now does this, but new mutation functions must follow the same pattern. *(lessons/pipeline-state-json-not-synced-on-archive.md)*
- # plugin-allowlist-must-be-updated-on-plugin-retire *(lessons/plugin-allowlist-must-be-updated-on-plugin-retire.md)*
- Retiring a plugin by renaming its directory to `.disabled` prevents OpenClaw from loading the plugin code, but `openclaw.json` still lists it in `plugins.allow`. When an agent is spawned, OpenClaw validates `plugins.allow` against actually-loadable plugins and fails with a config error if a listed plugin is missing. *(lessons/plugin-allowlist-must-be-updated-on-plugin-retire.md)*
- After renaming `pipeline-context` → `pipeline-context.disabled`, the next heartbeat attempted to dispatch the codex-engine-v3 architect agent. The agent failed to spawn because OpenClaw config validation rejected the stale `pipeline-context` entry in `plugins.allow`. Fixed by removing it from the allowlist. *(lessons/plugin-allowlist-must-be-updated-on-plugin-retire.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/plugins-have-presence-commands-are-fire-and-forget.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/render-engine-agents-are-in-it-not-calling-it.md)*
- instance:main sage session-key agent-rename openclaw *(lessons/sage-agent-session-key-stale-after-rename.md)*
- # sage-agent-session-key-stale-after-rename *(lessons/sage-agent-session-key-stale-after-rename.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/sage-agent-session-key-stale-after-rename.md)*
- # Lesson: OpenClaw Agent CLI Uses `main` Session, Not Group Session *(lessons/session-reset-targets-main-not-group.md)*
- `openclaw agent --agent <name> --message <msg>` delivers to the `agent:{name}:main` session key, NOT the `agent:{name}:telegram:group:{id}` session key. *(lessons/session-reset-targets-main-not-group.md)*
- Resetting only the group session left old handoff messages in the main session. The agent woke up, found three pipeline handoffs queued, and processed all three in one session — defeating the one-at-a-time gate. *(lessons/session-reset-targets-main-not-group.md)*
- `reset_agent_session()` must reset BOTH: *(lessons/session-reset-targets-main-not-group.md)*
- `agent:{name}:main` — the CLI session *(lessons/session-reset-targets-main-not-group.md)*
- `agent:{name}:telegram:group:{id}` — the group chat session *(lessons/session-reset-targets-main-not-group.md)*
- When debugging agent behavior, always check which session key the delivery mechanism actually uses. `openclaw gateway call sessions.list --json` shows all sessions with their keys. *(lessons/session-reset-targets-main-not-group.md)*
- if 'architect' in s.get('key', ''): *(lessons/session-reset-targets-main-not-group.md)*
- print(s['key'], s['sessionId'][:12]) *(lessons/session-reset-targets-main-not-group.md)*
- `R edit` uses `--set key=value` for frontmatter updates. List fields like `downstream=[lesson/foo, memory/bar]` contain spaces inside brackets. *(lessons/shell-splits-unquoted-list-args.md)*
- **Any CLI that accepts structured values (lists, JSON, YAML) as arguments must defend against shell word-splitting.** Don't rely on users quoting correctly — pre-process argv to rejoin split tokens. *(lessons/shell-splits-unquoted-list-args.md)*
- Fixed in `edit_primitive.py` with `_rejoin_list_args()` — detects unclosed `[` and consumes tokens until `]` *(lessons/shell-splits-unquoted-list-args.md)*
- Any future CLI that accepts list/structured `--set` values should use the same pattern *(lessons/shell-splits-unquoted-list-args.md)*
- Same class of bug applies to JSON values, paths with spaces, or any value containing shell metacharacters *(lessons/shell-splits-unquoted-list-args.md)*
- Test CLI tools with unquoted complex values, not just simple ones *(lessons/shell-splits-unquoted-list-args.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/soul-condensation-preserves-latent-nuance.md)*
- # Stacking Specialist Micro-Networks Is a Dead End *(lessons/stacking-specialists-is-dead-end.md)*
- Combining three event-detection SNN specialists (CrashDetector, RallyDetector, VolSpikeDetector) via logistic regression stacking **does not produce a useful direction predictor.** The shuffled-labels null model (50.55% accuracy, -0.62 Sharpe) is statistically indistinguishable from the best real stacker (51.93%, -0.84 Sharpe). Every real experiment has negative net Sharpe. *(lessons/stacking-specialists-is-dead-end.md)*
- ## Why It Fails — Three Structural Problems *(lessons/stacking-specialists-is-dead-end.md)*
- VolSpikeDetector has highest individual AUC (0.656) but is direction-agnostic — using it alone (49.74%) is worse than majority baseline *(lessons/stacking-specialists-is-dead-end.md)*
- Crash+Rally together (50.93%) ≈ full stacker without VolSpike — vol spikes don't predict direction *(lessons/stacking-specialists-is-dead-end.md)*
- Abstention produces zero coverage in 12/15 experiments — stacker probabilities are clustered near 0.5 *(lessons/stacking-specialists-is-dead-end.md)*
- The V3 Scheme B reference (52.0%, +0.45 Sharpe) is strictly superior to all stacking variants *(lessons/stacking-specialists-is-dead-end.md)*
- Composition at the **prediction level** (stacking probabilities) doesn't work when individual detectors are weak and correlated. Composition should happen at the **architectural level** (multi-scale temporal layers within a single SNN). *(lessons/stacking-specialists-is-dead-end.md)*
- `subprocess.run()` returns normally even when the command fails (exit code 1). No exception is raised. So `papermill_available` was set to `True` even though papermill wasn't installed. The runner then tried to use papermill and failed. *(lessons/subprocess-run-doesnt-raise-on-failure.md)*
- Always check `returncode`: *(lessons/subprocess-run-doesnt-raise-on-failure.md)*
- Or use `check=True` to make it raise `CalledProcessError` on non-zero exit. *(lessons/subprocess-run-doesnt-raise-on-failure.md)*
- This is a general Python gotcha: `subprocess.run()` only raises exceptions for OS-level failures (command not found, timeout), NOT for non-zero exit codes. Any "is this tool installed?" check that relies on try/except around `subprocess.run()` without `check=True` will silently pass. *(lessons/subprocess-run-doesnt-raise-on-failure.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/task-auto-archive-follows-downstream-work.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/three-context-path-redundancy.md)*
- ## What Works (Updated) *(lessons/tiny-snn-gpu-parallelism.md)*
- **12+ workers on T4:** GIL contention on CPU-side tensor slicing makes more threads counterproductive. *(lessons/tiny-snn-gpu-parallelism.md)*
- **`gpu_cleanup()` inside hot loops:** Acts as a global synchronization barrier across all threads. *(lessons/tiny-snn-gpu-parallelism.md)*
- The optimal GPU strategy depends on **model size relative to GPU capacity**, not just GPU type. For tiny models (<1MB), maximize **batch size first**, then use **minimal parallelism** (2 workers) to overlap CPU prep with GPU compute. More Python threads ≠ more GPU throughput when the GIL makes CPU-side prep sequential. *(lessons/tiny-snn-gpu-parallelism.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/token-ids-affect-attention-quality-not-just-count.md)*
- Since `threshold` was registered as a `torch.nn.Buffer`, PyTorch raises `TypeError: cannot assign 'float' as buffer 'threshold' (torch.nn.Buffer, torch.Tensor or None expected)`. This crashed every SNN experiment that used threshold annealing — the same error repeated across all folds and configs. *(lessons/torch-buffer-requires-tensor-assignment.md)*
- **Never assign a raw Python scalar to a `torch.nn.Buffer`.** Use in-place tensor operations: `.fill_()`, `.copy_()`, or `torch.tensor()` wrapping. *(lessons/torch-buffer-requires-tensor-assignment.md)*
- When writing or reviewing any code that modifies registered buffers (thresholds, betas, running stats), always use tensor-safe operations: *(lessons/torch-buffer-requires-tensor-assignment.md)*
- This applies to all `register_buffer()` parameters across SNN models — not just thresholds. Builders should treat buffer modification the same as parameter modification: always tensor ops. *(lessons/torch-buffer-requires-tensor-assignment.md)*
- # use-scaffold-then-edit-not-overwrite *(lessons/use-scaffold-then-edit-not-overwrite.md)*
- Creating two new decision primitives (phase2-human-gate, clock-cycles-over-tokens). Used `R create decision` to scaffold, then tried `Edit` tool to replace body content — but guessed the template markers wrong (assumed `<!-- comment -->` instead of actual `_italic prompts_`). Fell back to `Write` which overwrote the entire file, bypassing the scaffold pattern. *(lessons/use-scaffold-then-edit-not-overwrite.md)*
- `Write` (full overwrite) wastes the scaffold and violates clock-cycles-over-tokens — the scaffold already did the structural work, overwriting it re-does that work with tokens. The `Edit` tool failed because I didn't read the scaffold output first to learn the exact placeholder text. *(lessons/use-scaffold-then-edit-not-overwrite.md)*
- Always work WITH the scaffold: `R create` → `R edit --set` for frontmatter → `Read` the file → `Edit` body sections using exact placeholder text. Never `Write`-overwrite a scaffolded file. *(lessons/use-scaffold-then-edit-not-overwrite.md)*
- 2. `R edit "name" --set key=value` — frontmatter updates (clock cycles) *(lessons/use-scaffold-then-edit-not-overwrite.md)*
- _When does this lesson apply? What should change going forward?_ *(lessons/verify-notebook-paths-resolve-before-automation.md)*
- All three agents (architect, critic, builder) now use sessions_send with timeoutSeconds:0 for inter-agent communication. Session keys hardcoded in AGENT_SOUL.md and ANALYSIS_AGENT_ROLES.md. Pattern: complete stage → run pipeline_update.py → sessions_send next agent → post group chat update. No spawning new agents — use running instances. agents protocol sessions-send *(memory/entries/2026-03-17_033425_all-three-agents-architect-critic-builde.md)*
- V4 experiment total architecture failure: spike-count readout caused dead output neurons in >85% of 96 runs. V3 used membrane potential (continuous gradients), V4 switched to spike count (discrete, threshold-gated). Groups 5-6 magnitude: 100% abstention. Encoding comparison invalidated by output confound. V5 proposal: membrane readout fix, same matrix. 4 lessons created. v4 analysis failure *(memory/entries/2026-03-17_033432_v4-experiment-total-architecture-failure.md)*
- MANDATORY GATE: Never start a fresh notebook version until minimum 2 phases of analysis are complete. Phase 1 autonomous + Phase 2 human-directed are the minimum. The interference pattern between Phase 1 findings and Shael Phase 2 input can yield surprising results — premature conclusions from Phase 1 alone miss signal. What looks like failure may not be once human perspective is applied. pipeline analysis methodology *(memory/entries/2026-03-17_045502_mandatory-gate-never-start-a-fresh-noteb.md)*
- Agent workspace structure discovered: Each agent has own workspace (~/.openclaw/workspace-{agent}/) with custom AGENTS.md, SOUL.md, IDENTITY.md (files), but SYMLINKED shared directories: SNN_research, skills, scripts, templates, pipelines, tasks, lessons, decisions. Agents do NOT have MEMORY.md or memory/ from main — memory is coordinator-only context (per AGENTS.md guidance for group/shared contexts). BOOTSTRAP.md files still present in agent workspaces (should clean up eventually). agents workspace architecture *(memory/entries/2026-03-17_134119_agent-workspace-structure-discovered-eac.md)*
- Built multi-agent memory system. Each agent (architect, critic, builder) gets own memory/ dir with rolling 7-day logs. Scripts updated: log_memory.py (--workspace flag), consolidate_memories.py (--all-agents), new daily_agent_memory.py (midnight cron — consolidates each agent, summarizes to main daily log, archives >7 days), new agent_memory_update.py (per-session capture), pipeline_update.py auto-triggers memory after every complete/block. weekly_knowledge_sync.py enhanced with --all-agents for cross-agent synthesis. Cron: daily 00:05 UTC, weekly Monday 3AM. agents memory infrastructure *(memory/entries/2026-03-17_134119_built-multi-agent-memory-system-each-age.md)*
- Major session: Built three infrastructure systems. (1) v4-deep-analysis pipeline launched using dedicated OpenClaw agent instances via sessions_send orchestration — first test of multi-agent pipeline with persistent bots instead of subagents. (2) Mandatory Phase 2 analysis gate established (Shael directive) — never start new notebook version until analysis pipeline completes BOTH Phase 1 + Phase 2. Encoded in templates/analysis_pipeline.md, templates/pipeline.md, ANALYSIS_AGENT_ROLES.md, lessons/. (3) #phase2 tag convention — Shael drops feedback tagged #phase2 {version} anywhere, coordinator crystallizes into direction file, agents read it on Phase 2 cold-start. infrastructure pipeline orchestration *(memory/entries/2026-03-17_134119_major-session-built-three-infrastructure.md)*
- Phase 2 cold-start protocol: Agent context may rotate between Phase 1 and Phase 2. Every agent starting Phase 2 MUST read: (1) pipeline_builds/{version}_phase2_shael_direction.md — primary input, (2) Phase 1 notebook for context, (3) Phase 1 architect design for methodology, (4) pipeline state JSON. Analysis notebooks can reuse CUDA stream patterns from builder pipeline for GPU work on Colab (ThreadPoolExecutor + torch.cuda.Stream, batch_size 4096, fp32 only). pipeline analysis phase2 *(memory/entries/2026-03-17_134119_phase-2-cold-start-protocol-agent-contex.md)*
- Created R CLI at ~/.local/bin/belam — unified workspace command. Subcommands: pipelines/pipeline/tasks/lessons/decisions/projects/analyze/log/consolidate/build/notebooks/conversations/knowledge-sync/status. Shortcuts: pl p t l d pj s a nb conv ks cons. 'R analyze <ver>' auto-finds analysis pipelines. Works from any directory. cli infrastructure *(memory/entries/2026-03-17_144639_created-belam-cli-at-localbinbelam-unifi.md)*
- Built full workspace portability system. (1) R CLI at ~/.local/bin/belam — unified workspace command with subcommands for pipelines, primitives, memory, experiments, notebooks, status. Shortcuts: pl p t l d pj s a nb conv ks cons. (2) pipeline_update.py auto-bumps frontmatter status via STATUS_BUMPS dict on every stage transition — agents no longer need manual status calls. (3) pipeline_dashboard.py — live CLI monitor with --watch mode. (4) sync_knowledge_repo.py (R sync) — syncs all reproducible artifacts to CodexOperator/openclaw-knowledge repo: core docs, agent workspace configs, research docs, all scripts, templates, primitives, skills, R CLI. Dry run by default. (5) Knowledge repo README has full 7-step bootstrap guide for restoring on new machines. All agent-facing docs (AGENT_SOUL.md, ANALYSIS_AGENT_ROLES.md, pipelines SKILL.md, TOOLS.md) updated with R CLI references. All primitive templates have cli: field. infrastructure cli knowledge-repo *(memory/entries/2026-03-17_151007_built-full-workspace-portability-system.md)*
- Flattened directory structure: SNN_research/machinelearning/ → machinelearning/ (top level). Archived simple v4-analysis pipeline, keeping only v4-deep-analysis. Updated all path references across ~40 files (workspace + knowledge-repo + agent workspaces). Agent symlinks updated from SNN_research → machinelearning. infrastructure refactor *(memory/entries/2026-03-17_151632_flattened-directory-structure-snn-resear.md)*
- Full workspace portability now includes memory. R sync captures all 4 memory stores (main + architect/critic/builder) into knowledge-repo/memory/{name}/. README bootstrap guide updated to 8 steps with memory restore for both main workspace (step 2) and agent workspaces (step 6). Complete restore: clone openclaw-knowledge (infrastructure + memory + skills) + clone machinelearning (research data + notebooks + pipeline state) → everything wakes with continuity. infrastructure portability memory *(memory/entries/2026-03-17_152800_full-workspace-portability-now-includes.md)*
- Upgraded heartbeat from flat checklist to context-aware orchestrator. New templates/heartbeat.md contains decision framework, script reference, gate rules, task-to-pipeline mapping, anti-patterns. HEARTBEAT.md restructured: Task 1 is now pipeline/task orchestration (spawn pipelines for eligible tasks, check gates, unblock non-gated work). Non-gated tasks (specialist ensemble, scheme B validation) can now proceed independently of v4 analysis gate. Infrastructure tasks can spawn focused sub-agents instead of full pipelines. *(memory/entries/2026-03-17_154428_upgraded-heartbeat-from-flat-checklist-t.md)*
- Major heartbeat upgrade session. (1) Upgraded heartbeat from flat checklist to context-aware orchestrator — templates/heartbeat.md is the decision framework (script refs, gate rules, task-to-pipeline mapping, anti-patterns), HEARTBEAT.md is the task list that references it. Sonnet reads orchestrator ref each cycle. (2) Phase 3 iteration chain protocol (Shael directive): main and analysis pipelines interleave strictly — main iter N → analysis iter Na,Nb,Nc → all clear → main iter N+1. Multiple analysis per main allowed, but next main blocked until analysis fully done. Encoded in pipeline.md, analysis_pipeline.md, heartbeat.md templates. (3) Standalone Colab notebooks dir (notebooks/standalone/) for non-pipeline tasks. (4) Fixed v4 pipeline frontmatter desync (status was phase2_build, should have been phase2_complete — same old pipeline_update.py bug). (5) Non-gated tasks (specialist ensemble, scheme B validation) now eligible for heartbeat to spawn independently. infrastructure heartbeat orchestration *(memory/entries/2026-03-17_164821_major-heartbeat-upgrade-session-1-upgrad.md)*
- Phase 2 direction received from Shael for v4-deep-analysis. 9 directions: (1) overtraining/epoch sensitivity (dry run > full run), (2) temperature/stochastic controls seeded by network state (pseudo-quantum), (3) true equilibrium OUTPUT (steady frequency differential, not just inputs), (4) softmax decoding, (5) threshold sensitivity (rare events + high threshold = death), (6) micro/nano regression targets (price %, volume, volume delta%), (7) rhythm neurons (keep-alive clock signal from earlier MNIST work), (8) sparse/selective connectivity (weights [0.1,10], pruning), (9) standard ANN benchmarks. Meta-theme: biological homeostasis — V5 should be 'biologically-informed homeostatic SNN' not just 'V4 with membrane fix.' Direction file: pipeline_builds/v4-deep-analysis_phase2_shael_direction.md. Pipeline advanced to analysis_phase2_architect, sent to architect agent. pipeline phase2 v4 *(memory/entries/2026-03-17_171127_phase-2-direction-received-from-shael-fo.md)*
- Built launch-pipeline skill + R kickoff CLI command. Added pipeline_created→architect_design to transition map. Updated launch_pipeline.py --kickoff to use orchestrator instead of raw sessions_send. Updated heartbeat template + HEARTBEAT.md for Sonnet to use R kickoff. Kicked off all 3 pipelines (build-equilibrium-snn, stack-specialists, validate-scheme-b) — architect acknowledged all 3, designing in parallel. infrastructure skill orchestration *(memory/entries/2026-03-17_234248_built-launch-pipeline-skill-belam-kickof.md)*
- Orchestrator now auto-consolidates agent memory at every handoff boundary. Added --learnings flag to complete/block commands. The script writes directly to the calling agent's memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md AND runs log_memory.py for indexed entries. Agents no longer need to manually remember to save memory — the orchestrator guarantees it happens before session ends. Also added AGENT_WORKSPACES mapping for all agent workspace paths. *(memory/entries/2026-03-18_143808_orchestrator-now-auto-consolidates-agent.md)*
- CRITICAL FIX: reset_agent_session() was resetting the wrong session. Was resetting agent:{name}:telegram:group:{id} (group session) but openclaw agent CLI uses agent:{name}:main. Fixed to reset BOTH session keys. This was why the architect processed all 3 pipelines in one session — old handoff messages were queued in the main session and never cleared. Also added session reset to checkpoint_and_resume flow. *(memory/entries/2026-03-18_170835_critical-fix-reset-agent-session-was-res.md)*
- Major infrastructure session 2026-03-18: (1) Upgraded architect/critic/builder from Sonnet→Opus. (2) Orchestrator overhaul: fresh UUID4 sessions per handoff, 10-min timeout, auto-memory consolidation via --learnings flag, checkpoint-and-resume on timeout (up to 5 cycles). (3) CRITICAL BUG FIX: reset_agent_session() was resetting telegram:group session but openclaw agent CLI uses agent:{name}:main session — fixed to reset BOTH. (4) Built pipeline_autorun.py for event-driven lifecycle: gate checking + stall detection + one-pipeline-at-a-time enforcement. Wired into R CLI as 'R autorun'. (5) Updated HEARTBEAT.md to call autorun script instead of LLM decision-making. (6) Updated pipelines and launch-pipeline skills with new orchestrator protocol. (7) All three stalled pipelines (build-equilibrium-snn, stack-specialists, validate-scheme-b) are now actively progressing through Phase 1. (8) Remaining issue: validate-scheme-b still needs builder work — will be picked up by next autorun stall cycle. infrastructure *(memory/entries/2026-03-18_173356_major-infrastructure-session-2026-03-18.md)*
- Added stale session lock detection to pipeline_autorun.py. Three-tier recovery: (1) Lock staleness check every heartbeat — 5min threshold, detects dead PIDs (clear immediately) and hung processes (SIGTERM/SIGKILL/clear). Runs BEFORE gate/stall checks since stale locks block everything. (2) Gate check (existing). (3) Stall recovery at 2h (existing). New --check-locks flag for standalone use. After clearing locks, auto-resets agent sessions for clean dispatch. infrastructure autorun resilience *(memory/entries/2026-03-18_183716_added-stale-session-lock-detection-to-pi.md)*
- Created decision primitives for all 4 specialist skills: derivative-specialist-skill, predictionmarket-specialist-skill, quant-infrastructure-skill, quant-workflow-skill. Every workspace skill now has a corresponding primitive with skill: cross-reference. Full mapping: derivative-specialist→derivative-specialist-skill, launch-pipeline→agent-session-isolation, orchestration→orchestration-architecture, pipelines→agent-trio-architecture, predictionmarket-specialist→predictionmarket-specialist-skill, quant-infrastructure→quant-infrastructure-skill, quant-workflow→quant-workflow-skill. skills primitives knowledge *(memory/entries/2026-03-18_192319_created-decision-primitives-for-all-4-sp.md)*
- Convention established: every workspace skill MUST have a corresponding decision primitive with a skill: cross-reference field in frontmatter. The primitive captures the WHY (architectural rationale, alternatives considered, consequences) while the SKILL.md captures the HOW (usage, commands, patterns). Primitives use naming pattern: {skill-name}-skill.md for dedicated ones, or existing decisions that naturally map (e.g. pipelines→agent-trio-architecture). When creating new skills, always create the primitive alongside it. skills primitives convention *(memory/entries/2026-03-18_192651_convention-established-every-workspace-s.md)*
- Built embed_primitives.py — auto-generates primitive index sections in AGENTS.md and MEMORY.md bootstrap files. AGENTS.md gets categorized list with usage guidance (when/why to read each primitive). MEMORY.md gets full YAML structural index. Both stay within 18k char budget. Wired into: R consolidate (auto-runs after consolidation), R embed-primitives (standalone), HEARTBEAT.md Task 7. Uses HTML comment markers for idempotent section replacement. infrastructure memory primitives *(memory/entries/2026-03-18_200633_built-embed-primitivespy-auto-generates.md)*
- Extended MEMORY_CONTENT embed to include recent daily consolidated entries (today + yesterday full, day-before ★★★★+ only) alongside weekly/monthly rollups. Deduplicates entries across consolidation runs within a day. Budget bumped to 40k chars (currently ~30k used). New sessions now wake with 3 days of operational context + medium-term patterns inline — zero extra file reads needed for recent context. infrastructure memory boot *(memory/entries/2026-03-18_215728_extended-memory-content-embed-to-include.md)*
- Optimized embed_primitives.py output formats: YAML→ASCII trees for primitive index (39% smaller) and memory hierarchy (49% smaller). AGENTS.md also tightened (7%). Total ~900 tokens saved per boot across all agents. Also fixed bug where tasks section used project path variable. Convention: prefer ASCII tree format over YAML for structural indexes — more token-efficient and equally scannable for LLMs. infrastructure memory optimization *(memory/entries/2026-03-18_220649_optimized-embed-primitivespy-output-form.md)*
- Major workspace infrastructure session: (1) Optimized embed_primitives.py — YAML→ASCII tree format for primitive index (39% smaller) and memory hierarchy (49% smaller). (2) Stripped embedded memory content from MEMORY.md system prompt — saves ~5,200 tokens per boot (agents read daily files on-demand instead). MEMORY.md went from 31K→7.2K chars. (3) Added trigger_embed.py with 5s debounce — wired into log_memory, consolidate_memories, weekly/monthly consolidation. Indexes auto-update on every write. (4) Built R create CLI — 'R create lesson/decision/task/project/skill' with proper frontmatter scaffolding, auto-triggers embed. Skill creation auto-generates both SKILL.md and decision primitive (skill-primitive-pairing convention). (5) Built R edit CLI — fuzzy-match primitives, --set key=value for frontmatter updates, auto-triggers embed. (6) Created projects/agent-roster.md — single source of truth for all 4 agents (coordinator/architect/critic/builder), models, workspaces, sessions, conventions. infrastructure cli primitives optimization *(memory/entries/2026-03-18_225239_major-workspace-infrastructure-session-1.md)*
- Primitives are the universal organizational unit. Everything gets its own primitive file with YAML frontmatter: lessons/, decisions/, tasks/, projects/, pipelines/, commands/, skills/. All auto-indexed in AGENTS.md and MEMORY.md boot trees via embed_primitives.py. TOOLS.md reduced to consciousness tools + environment notes only — no more command tables or skill references (those live in their own primitive dirs). New primitives created via 'R create <type>' which scaffolds frontmatter and triggers index rebuild. This is the workspace's fundamental design principle: if it matters, it's a primitive with a file. infrastructure primitives architecture convention *(memory/entries/2026-03-19_005231_primitives-are-the-universal-organizatio.md)*
- Session 2026-03-19 00:52-02:55 UTC — V4 Deep Analysis execution and Phase 1 revision kickoff. Shael requested: execute v4-deep-analysis Phase 2 notebook, analyze results, create findings doc, and kick off Phase 1 revisions for all active pipelines sequentially. Steps completed: (1) Executed v4 deep analysis notebook (146 cells, all passed) — loaded 96 result records from 6 group pkl files at notebooks/snn_crypto_predictor_v4_pkl/. (2) Committed + pushed results (commit 235d4ac). (3) Created analysis findings doc (research/v4_deep_analysis_findings.md) with pipeline-specific revision context for each of the 3 active pipelines. Committed (ffe27b1). (4) Fixed bug in pipeline_orchestrate.py — write_handoff() was receiving a string instead of dict from orchestrate_revise(). (5) Kicked off 'R revise build-equilibrium-snn' with full V4 findings context. Orchestrator autonomously steered the full revision cycle: architect designed revision (01:07) → critic reviewed design (01:13) → builder implemented (01:23) → critic code review approved 24/24 (01:34) → back to phase1_complete. (6) stack-specialists and validate-scheme-b still at original phase1_complete — revisions not yet triggered, pending Shael direction. Shael also asked about pkl files on desktop — confirmed they're result records not weights, repo had all data, pipeline uses text conclusions not raw pkl. The automated orchestrator handled the entire 5-stage revision loop without intervention once kicked. pipeline revision v4-analysis build-equilibrium-snn orchestration *(memory/entries/2026-03-19_030405_session-2026-03-19-0052-0255-utc-v4-deep.md)*
- Built revision queue system for pipeline_autorun.py. New check_pending_revisions() scans pipeline_builds/*_revision_request.md files (YAML frontmatter with version, context_file, section, priority). Autorun picks up highest-priority request, loads context from the referenced findings doc (with optional section extraction), calls orchestrate_revise(), then deletes the request file. Integrates into the existing check order: locks → gates → revisions → stalls. One pipeline at a time respected throughout. Created revision requests for stack-specialists and validate-scheme-b pointing to v4_deep_analysis_findings.md. CLI: --check-revisions flag for standalone use. HEARTBEAT.md updated. infrastructure orchestration revision autorun *(memory/entries/2026-03-19_031427_built-revision-queue-system-for-pipeline.md)*
- Completed workspace refactor — three workstreams. (1) Knowledge skill migration: 4 knowledge-type skills (derivative-specialist, predictionmarket-specialist, quant-infrastructure, quant-workflow) migrated from skills/*/SKILL.md to knowledge/*.md with primitive:knowledge frontmatter. Reference files merged inline. Old skill dirs removed. 3 operational skills remain (orchestration, pipelines, launch-pipeline). embed_primitives.py and create_primitive.py updated to handle knowledge type. (2) R audit command: scripts/audit_primitives.py with 5 checks — orphaned commands, stale skill refs, cross-ref integrity, skill→decision pairing, duplicate detection. --fix mode for auto-remediation. Wired as R audit (R au). (3) Auto-linking in R create: new primitives auto-detect related skills by tag/category overlap and append cross-references. --no-link to skip, --skill for explicit targeting. infrastructure primitives refactor knowledge audit *(memory/entries/2026-03-19_033706_completed-workspace-refactor-three-works.md)*
- Session 2026-03-19 03:01-04:10 UTC — Workspace refactor session with Shael. Three workstreams completed: (1) Knowledge skill migration — 4 knowledge-type skills (derivative-specialist, predictionmarket-specialist, quant-infrastructure, quant-workflow) migrated from skills/*/SKILL.md to knowledge/*.md as primitive:knowledge type. Reference files merged inline. Old skill dirs removed. 3 operational skills remain (orchestration, pipelines, launch-pipeline). (2) R audit command — scripts/audit_primitives.py with 5 checks: orphaned commands, stale skill refs, cross-ref integrity, skill→decision pairing, duplicate detection. --fix mode for auto-remediation. (3) Auto-linking in R create — new primitives auto-detect related skills by tag overlap and append cross-references. Also during session: revision queue kicked for stack-specialists and validate-scheme-b (autorun picked them up). Conversation exported to machinelearning/snn_applied_finance/conversations/2026-03-19_coordinator_a3571f35.md session infrastructure refactor knowledge audit *(memory/entries/2026-03-19_041328_session-2026-03-19-0301-0410-utc-workspa.md)*
